ext-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent has 449 primary schools, of which 55 are academies (40 are new sponsored academies and 15 are stand-alone converter ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ademies, not part of a chain)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are currently 67 secondary academies (including 3 Free Schools), equivalent two thirds of secondary schools in Kent. 15 of these are traditional sponsored academies (sustained under-performance in areas of disadvantage).  Five are new sponsored acade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mies (following an Ofsted judgement putting them in Category).  The remaining 47 are converter academies, whose performance was judged by Ofsted to be good or outstanding at the time of conversion.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Irrespective of whether academies were sponsored or co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nverter, Kent has not seen a narrowing of the achievement gap for FSM children, compared to maintained schools, either at primary or secondary level. The FSM gap for academies is equal to maintained primary schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academies and Free Schools, through Ken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t School Collaborative Partnerships are encouraged to work with neighbouring schools and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authority (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">colleagues to get the most out of the pupil premium to narrow the achievement gap.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the support of the LA, Kent schools and their Collabora</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tive Partnerships (of which there are 60 involving 500 schools) are now intensively focusing on narrowing the gap for vulnerable groups.  The LA expects academies to focus on (in the same way as LA maintained school colleagues), ensuring that vulnerable gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oups are identified, strategies personalised and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upil </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">remium monies effectively targeted to appropriate strategies.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ounty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ouncil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (KCC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> autumn term round of Headteacher Briefings (to which all category of schools are invited) by the Corporate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Director for Education, Learning and Skills focused on closing the achievement gap – what the performance data is telling us, what strategies are effective (best practice locally and nationally shared) and which schools are using the pupil premium funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effectively to narrow the achievement gaps.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC’s weekly E-Bulletin for all schools on 28 November 2013, focused on closing the gap and provided information on effective strategies. KCC is developing a range of good practice case studies in partnership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with a number of the schools that are having the biggest impact on this key issue, and with the help of some schools we are also developing a staff development programme to support the adoption of the most effective practices. We will launch this work in F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ebruary 2014. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There seems to be limited evidence that academies per se are having a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">greater impact on narrowing gaps and improving outcomes for disadvantaged pupils. Individual schools make more or less of a difference depending on the quality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> teaching and other intervention strategies to improve outcomes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research from Machin and Silva (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">School Structure, School Autonomy and the Tail, Centre for Economic Performance Special Paper No. 29, LSE, 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">), suggest that academies had not yet helped low</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attaining pupils.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This paper shows that improved attainment centres on higher attainers. It also cites research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(Wilson, J (2011) Are England’s Academies more Inclusive or More ‘Exclusive’? The Impact of Institutional Change on the Pupil Profile of Schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">ls. CEE Discussion Paper 125)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which shows a 12.5% reduction in pupils on free school meals, attending (traditional sponsored) academies compared with the schools they replaced. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More widely in terms of overall pupil achievement, recent research has found that there is no direct correlation between being an academy and improved attainment levels, reflected in Ofsted judgements.  The critical characteristic to raising attainment in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a school is the individual capacity of the school leadership. Many sponsored academies are improving the quality of education and pupil outcomes, as they have often replaced very poorly performing schools.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is interesting to note that research commiss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ioned by the L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssociation (LGA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into GCSE results at both academies and maintained schools, published by the NFER in November 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Analysis of academy school performance in the 2011 and 2012 GCSEs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">),</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> states that academies do not necessaril</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y outperform non-academies at GCSE. The study found that in analysing school-level GCSE data since 2007, there is no significant improvement in the rate of improvement of GCSE results for academies over and above the rate of improvement in all schools. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggested characteristics of a school, such as strong leadership or the quality of teaching, are more likely to be responsible for differences seen, rather than the school's organisational structure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">uestion 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent LA has developed a good working relationship with the DfE in managing the conversion of schools that wish to become academies and in making arrangements for some schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be sponsored as academies as a result of poor performance or an inadequate inspection judgement. The LA is now helpfully at a point where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identifying local sponsors for Kent schools that require an academy solution. At the same time the LA has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">good working relationship with some, but not all, academy chains that sponsor academies in Kent. It is disappointing that some chains do not respond to our invitation to work more closely together or to offers to help academy chain schools that are still s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">truggling to improve. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of what’s not always working well, we would cite the following issues. The proposed sponsor sometimes makes considerable extra demands upon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the LA and its financial and capital resources towards the end of the process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ansfer of a school to an academy chain. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This slows down, and can hinder</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the conversion process and can interfere with the urgent school improvement work required.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The issuing of an Academy Order can therefore be significantly delayed. In one instance the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sponsor pulled out at the very end of the process, leaving the school and the local authority without a solution. Sponsors need to be better at due diligence and be committed from the outset.  Considerable public resource and LA Officer time is expended un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">necessarily waiting for sponsors to decide to proceed with their initial interest. The LA is concerned about the lack of engagement at the earliest opportunity regarding new Free School proposals.  As the strategic commissioner of new school provision, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> LA would welcome early involvement in free school proposals to create new pupil provision in areas of evidenced need.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present we have five Free Schools open in Kent.  All are in areas of socio-economic advantage, rather than growing diversity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">choice in disadvantaged areas of need.  There appears to be ‘middle class capture’ of the Free Schools process, in order to create new capacity in areas that do not necessarily need school places.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">uestion 3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in interveni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ng in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is concern about the oversight by the DfE of under-performing and failing academies. The issuing of a warning notice is a limited form of interventio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and support. In Kent, failing academies do not appear to be being turned around as fast as they should be when they are continuing to perform poorly.  For example, in 2005 a failing secondary high school, in area of socio-economic disadvantage was conver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ted to a traditional sponsored academy.  Since that time, it has been the subject of an Ofsted Category twice and to date, the principal sponsor remains and the Academy Trust do not appear to have been transparently held to account by the Secretary of Stat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.  No Warning Notice has been served on this Academy Trust to date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">uestion 4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">al schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent County Council plays a strong role in school improvement, continues to relate and work with all schools irrespective of their status and monitors the outcomes for children and young people being educated in the county. Where academy schools are under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">performing and need to improve at a faster rate we offer support. A good number of academies buy back the services of the local authority. We continue to relate to all schools in carrying out our responsibilities for admissions, SEN, exclusions and the com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">missioning of new school places. We recognise the need for the LA as a strong ‘Middle Tier’ between all schools and the Secretary of State.  We would like more opportunity to hold under-performing academies to account for the outcomes they are achieving fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r Kent children and families. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present KCC is unclear how the LA can be held to account for the performance of academies beyond outlining our concerns to the trusts and governing bodies concerned, and to the Secretary of State. This is unsatisfactory. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC has no powers or funding to tackle underperformance in academies, nonetheless as an LA, we have been inviting academies and free schools to work with the family of Kent schools through the 60 School Collaborative Partnerships established since 2012 t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o create a sustainable, self-improving school system. This is working well and many academy schools are supporting other schools to improve. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around two thirds of all academies nationally now are converter academies (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i.e.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> good or outstanding schools). KCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expects these high performing academies to commit to supporting under-performing neighbouring schools, and while most schools respond well, KCC would welcome support to persuade government to make this requirement a more robust obligatory component in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funding agreement when schools convert to academies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In order to support academies and monitor their outcomes, Kent School Improvement Service offers all academies two consultation visits per year. Most schools take up this offer with some paying for ad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ditional commissioned school improvement support.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where an academy is experiencing difficulties and improvement is not evident, the LA writes to the Principal and the Academy Trust outlining our concerns and support we are able to provide.  If there is no positive response, KCC alerts Ofsted and the Secre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tary of State. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent County Council has continued to play a strong role in education as the middle tier. There is a strong shared vision with schools and close partnership with schools. We see this as essential for improving educational outcomes and the q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uality of schools, as well as for the integration of children’s services. We see the potential atomisation and fragmentation of the education system as a serious risk to delivering joined up early intervention and prevention services for vulnerable childre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and young people, and to making the best local strategic arrangements for pupils with special educational needs and those excluded from school. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bold Steps for Education Vision and Priorities for Improvement 2014-17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sets out how  KCC will work in partne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rship with  schools to create the conditions in which pupils experience the best learning and teaching, and where  their’ moral and intellectual development and confidence can flourish.  Bold Steps is a coherent strategy to effectively fulfil KCC’s respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ibilities, acting as the strategic advocate of a joint shared vision for education, learning and skills in Kent. As the legitimate democratic champion for children, parents and the communities of Kent this vision sets out how KCC will as the middle tier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">romote excellence across the system by ensuring:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All stakeholders are brought together and have a voice</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A relentless focus on high standards and tackling underperformance through a framework for robust school to school support </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A sufficiently planned supply of high quality early years and school places, as well as appropriate post 16 pathways </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provision of commissioned high quality support for vulnerable children to achieve positive outcomes, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Effective, collective account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ability with schools for the outcomes of all children and young people in Kent. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tension between accountability and autonomy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">4.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">School autonomy is a good thing if it is within a system that allows cooperation and support for weak schools.  School autonomy </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">also needs to exist within a system of strong, external accountability.  If autonomy leads to a free for all, then the school system </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">fragment, the difference in outcomes between schools grows</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and standards fall overall.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">(</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Andreas Schleicher, Head of </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Education Analysis for the OECD, in a report published on 13 September 2011, ‘Education at a Glance’)</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the big</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gest challenges</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> school system is that </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LAs</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> legally</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> responsible for the education</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> performance</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of all children, but have pow</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to intervene locally in </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintained schools only. There is no organisational regional structure to relate to about </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">failing academies and free schools</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, apart from the D</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and individual trusts that may themselves be lacking capacity to support the neces</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sary improvements. The DfE does not respond constructively when the LA expresses concern about the performance of some academies. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC supports the </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GA in its call for LAs to be empowered to intervene early in struggling schools regardless of whether they </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are academies or local authority-maintained schools:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"Councils are restlessly ambitious for all children in their local area whatever type of school they attend but have to jump through many hoops before they are allowed to intervene where there are sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s of failure. As Ofsted increases its inspection of councils' role in improving education, councils need a free hand to intervene early in struggling schools and to reassure mums and dads that their child's one chance at education will give them the best s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">tart in life."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(Cllr. David Simmonds, Chairman of LGA's Children and Young People Board, 13 November 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But to do this LAs need to remain sustainable in their capacity to support school improvement.  Shifts in education policy, power, accountability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and funding are increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> making it more difficult to maintain the capacity of some Councils to fulfil the statutory duty of ensuring the best possible education for all children in an area, irrespective of the type of school they attend.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is not timely to be designing unnecessary new regional bureaucracies to ensure proper oversight of the academy school system, about which there is little detail so far to provide the future proofing that is needed to secure high standards and continuous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improvement in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all academies and free schools. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">uestion 5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academy chains are a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant player but they are a small part of the education landscape and there are questions about their capacity and track record in bringing about the necessary improvements in poorly performing academies. Some are very successful, some not. It appear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s that some academy chains have been allowed to grow without sufficient regard to the quality of the provision they offer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of accountability, chains are accountable to their Trust and then the Secretary of State.  There is no local democratic acc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ountability, and this lack of transparency and accountability should be addressed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There is a need for a proper strategic relationship between the LA as commissioner and the major academy providers (whether national chains or more local groupings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">). This is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> something the LA seeks to achieve on the ground, but the current policy framework is not especially supportive of it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent announcement by Lord Nash, stating that academy chains will be inspected by Ofsted in the future is welcome, as long as judgements are made about their local impact and their level of accountability to the community they serve.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">uestion 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">e appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent is experiencing slow progress in respect of primary academy conversions. Few primary schools are attracted to academy status. In November 2013, there were 55 Kent primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademies out of 449 primary schools (12%).  Of the 55 primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademies, 15 are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stand-alone conversions but the other 40 are sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademies, consequent upon low performance and inadequate Ofsted Inspection judgements.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a further 20 schools with an Academy Order pending, with conversion likely to take place between De</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cember 2013 and May 2014. Some of these are church schools and will join diocesan multi-academy trusts, and some are under-performing schools. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">East Kent has the highest number of primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademies with 23 schools, compared to West Kent which has 8 primar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cademies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rush to convert to academy status may be over as the financial gains have diminished. Schools are pragmatic. A survey in 2012 conducted by the Schools Network found that 78% had converted in part because they believed they would be bette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r off financially.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schools are primarily focused on what can help them raise attainment. Some may judge that acquiring academy status supports this endeavour. Others schools may procure valuable services from the LA and use the LA’s collaborative struct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ures to secure support for teaching and learning and school improvement. In Kent, local soft and hard federations of schools have often been preferred by school governing bodies as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a more effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> route to school improvement, rather than through securing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academy status.  The Kent family of schools offers local flexibility, knowledge and expertise about what works, compared to a distant academy chain or central government support and control.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">uestion 7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nswer</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In some cases, where radical improvement and re-organisation are needed to respond to a history of failure and under-performance an academy sponsor solution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is appropriate, where it will bring significant additional capacity for improvement. KCC supports these solutions and values the opportunity to work with sponsors to bring these structural solutions to fruition, and have an on-going working relationship. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In other cases however, we have been able to broker a quicker solution for improvement by developing a hard federation with an outstanding local school or by brokering a soft federation, established through the Kent School Collaborative Partnerships who kn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ow each other’s capabilities and trust each other. In these cases we seek stronger and sometimes new school leadership and more effective governance, which often achieves a very quick turnaround and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sustainable upward trend in a school’s performance.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC prefers a more mixed approach with some flexibility. Often it seems the D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E is only inte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rested in one kind of solution.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>